title Read-fence vs jail-local keys: answering a live security question
prompt Keaton asked directly, no task attached: is it more secure for ai-jail to keep reading ~/.ssh and other real home dotfiles, or to deny that read entirely and reroute every relevant command to dedicated binaries/dotfiles living inside ~/urbit/ instead?
think this is a design question, not a task -- answered in prose rather than touching any file, per the collaboration rhythm's own distinction between mechanical next steps and design/value-model questions that deserve a named ruling before action.
think named the real exploit chain plainly: the macOS launcher's two current defaults -- reads open everywhere, network allowed by default -- combine into a full exfiltration path that needs no write at all. The write fence (repo + /tmp, deny elsewhere) that this session's own earlier tests proved solid protects against tampering with the host; it does nothing against a compromised agent reading a real private key and phoning it out over the already-open network.
think connected this directly to SOURCE.md's own Step 8 design for the Linux launcher (dedicated sandbox-only GPG key, copied SSH deploy keys, revocable, never the master identity) -- that pattern already names the right answer; the macOS GUI launcher just hasn't built the private-$HOME half of it yet, a gap the macOS guide already names but had understated the stakes of.
think framed the trade-off honestly rather than picking a side for Keaton: today's real-key-read approach is more convenient (no new keys to generate or register) and carries the larger blast radius (real identity exposed on compromise); dedicated jail-local keys cost setup effort and buy a small, revocable blast radius instead.
obs did not build the deny-read + dedicated-key sandbox this turn -- that reshapes the sandbox's own security model, which the collaboration rhythm names as exactly the kind of decision that earns a check-in rather than an assumed yes, even though Keaton is asking the question directly in this same session.
obs offered to build it next, explicitly, rather than leaving the question purely informational -- the real next step (macOS private-$HOME + jail-local SSH/GPG materials, mirroring SOURCE.md Step 8b/8c) is now named and waiting on Keaton's word.
file session-logs/20260714-074900_read-fence-vs-jail-local-keys-security-question.bron -- this log
recommend check-in -- Keaton's answer on whether to build the macOS private-$HOME + jail-local-keys hardening determines real, non-trivial next work (a Seatbelt profile change denying reads on ~/.ssh and ~/.gnupg, new dedicated keys generated and registered on both forges, and a SOURCE.md Step 8 macOS section written to match); this is a security-shape decision, not a mechanical continuation, so it waits for his word before any file changes.
